  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the higher accident rate of Google’s self‑driving cars is not due to faulty AI but to human drivers unfamiliar with the robots’ rigid, law‑abiding behavior. It critiques Google’s “always obey the rules” strategy, noting that strict compliance creates legal and ethical dilemmas (e.g., the trolley‑problem) and makes the vehicles poor traffic participants. The author proposes a tiered control system—precise law‑following, flexible traffic‑aware adjustments, and an emergency‑avoidance layer—to give autonomous cars more human‑like adaptability, and suggests visible warnings (red flashing LEDs) to alert human drivers. The tone is a mix of analytical critique and opinionated advocacy, aimed at engineers, policymakers, and tech‑savvy readers interested in autonomous‑vehicle safety and regulation.",
